{"key":"post-9580100","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>9580100</id>\n<content>I have no idea what you're trying to come up with.&amp;nbsp; You don't use steam to humidify a growing chamber or it will all end up as condensation on the walls.&amp;nbsp; You also don't want to heat a fruiting chamber for the same reason.&amp;nbsp; That's why we use them in normal room temperature, so the fruiting chamber is already at the temp preferred by mushrooms.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You also don't want wet mist falling on your substrate trays or cakes.&amp;nbsp; There must be evaporation of moisture from the substrate or fruiting performance is poor.&amp;nbsp; This means you want your cakes to begin drying out, and then you mist.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Massive amounts of fresh air is one of the top pinning triggers, which at 99% humidity will cause the desired evaporation of moisture from the substrate.&amp;nbsp; If you're growing in a tub, damp perlite in a shotgun terrarium will keep your humidity levels at the right spot for several weeks, which is more than enough for a cropping cycle.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;If you're using a mini-greenhouse, go with coolmist humidfiers or you can go low-tech and hang a wet towel or two inside the greenhouse, and change it/them out every few days with fresh towels.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>9580220</next>\n<prev>9579862</prev>\n<first>9535693</first>\n<last>9586112</last>\n<when>1231564436</when>\n<utime>01/10/09 07:13 AM</utime>\n</post>"}